fn sort(arr: list) {
    if arr.len() <= 1 {
        return;
    }
    if arr.len() == 2 {
        arr[0], arr[1] = arr[1], arr[0];
        return;
    }
    let pivot = partition(arr);
    sort(arr[..pivot]);
    sort(arr[pivot..]);
}

fn partition(arr: list) -> usize {
    let pivot = arr[0];
    let mut i = 0;
    for j in 1..arr.len() {
        if arr[j] < pivot {
            arr[i], arr[j] = arr[j], arr[i];
            i += 1;
        }
    }
    arr[i], arr[0] = arr[0], arr[i];
    i
}
```

Timsort is a hybrid sorting algorithm that combines the best features of insertion sort and merge sort. It has a good average-case performance and can be used to sort arrays of elements in many programming languages.

The `sort` function takes a list of integers as input and sorts it in ascending order. It uses the `partition` function to partition the list into smaller sub-lists, sorts them recursively, and then merges them back together.

The `partition` function selects the first element of the list as the pivot and uses two nested loops to partition the list into two sub-lists: one that contains elements smaller than the pivot and one that contains elements larger than the pivot. The function returns the index of the pivot in the sorted list.

